<br>
Everyone has feelings about what they believe. Some feelings are fact, some feelings are theories and others are just feelings with no basis other than they make perfect sense and you cannot imagin how others cannot see what you see. I have a feeling that fits into #3. I believe that everyone contains an energy (or spirit if you will) that leaves our body when we die and traveles interdimentionally until (or if) it decides to be reborn into another physical form (sortof like reincarnation with a twist). Is this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fact</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that this happens? Nope. Do <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> believe that it does? Sure. It is my belief. Who knows. Maybe some day, people will find evidence to support it and maybe evidence will be found to disprove it. Either way, I will accept the findings as scientific truth.<br>
<br>
I think that is what is hard for many people to accept with their beliefs in a diety is that there is some &quot;evidence&quot; (ie miracles or the seemingly unexplainable) that points to the existance of said diety. I have given this example to my dd when she starts asking questions: <br>
<br>
&quot;When you look at the night sky, you see stars, right? You know that the stars are really planets and burning fireballs that are millions of miles away. Right? Well, long ago, people did not have the knowledge or equipment to know this. They would come up with reasonable explanations to answer their questions. Some thought the stars were pin holes into heaven and others thought they were &quot;grains of sand stuck up in that big bluish black thing&quot; (Thanks to the lion king<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). They had no comprehension that it could be anything else and their reasons made perfect sense to them.&quot;<br>
<br>
IMO, people have created G-d to be an explaination for the unexplainable. The belief in G-d answers questions like &quot;How can life (an entire being) be created from two individual cells?&quot; or &quot;How can some people survive pancreatic (sp) cancer (only 5 in the US that I know of) when most people die?&quot; Must be a miracle... right? Now, being an agnostic, I really cannot prove that there is not a G-d and he doesn't have a hand in any of these miracles. If there is a G-d, he may. My point is that I cannot prove it either way. <br>
<br>
ok... I think I have digressed. Sorry if I have. *sigh* I am so ready to have this baby!! *wah*<br>
